00:00:41.610 --> 00:00:45.660
We have everybody here
by definition is special.

00:00:45.660 --> 00:00:48.920
I could go through everybody's
name, but that will take too long,

00:00:48.920 --> 00:00:52.250
so please excuse me
for not mentioning you

00:00:52.250 --> 00:00:54.220
but I'll just do it generically.

00:00:54.220 --> 00:00:56.740
So we are very pleased
that we have a number

00:00:56.740 --> 00:00:58.230
of members of Congress here.

00:00:58.230 --> 00:01:01.080
This is The Library of Congress,
after all, and the Congress

00:01:01.080 --> 00:01:03.630
and The Library of Congress
have a special relationship.

00:01:03.630 --> 00:01:06.380
Many members of Congress
have shown enormous interest

00:01:06.380 --> 00:01:07.680
in The Library of Congress.

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:09.920
I want to thank those members
who are here for doing that

00:01:09.920 --> 00:01:11.350
and for coming this evening.

00:01:11.350 --> 00:01:15.520
I also want to thank the supporters
of the Festival for many people

00:01:15.520 --> 00:01:18.680
who have done a lot to make this
possible financially and otherwise,

00:01:18.680 --> 00:01:21.630
I'll mention some in a
minute, but thank you.

00:01:21.630 --> 00:01:25.200 position:56%
I want to thank the Madison
Council, which is an arm, in effect,

00:01:25.200 --> 00:01:29.630
the affiliate of The Library of
Congress, which helps with support

00:01:29.630 --> 00:01:31.230
for The Library of
Congress, I want to thank them

00:01:31.230 --> 00:01:33.550
for their support of this event.

00:01:33.550 --> 00:01:35.550
I want to thank book lovers,

00:01:35.550 --> 00:01:39.310
and that includes everybody
here, people who love books.

00:01:39.310 --> 00:01:42.550
I also want to thank a special
person who is here this evening,

00:01:42.550 --> 00:01:46.270
the First Lady of Ruanda,
Jeannette Kagame, where is she?

00:01:46.270 --> 00:01:48.070
Jeannette, thank you.

00:01:48.070 --> 00:01:55.460
[ Applause ]

00:01:55.460 --> 00:01:59.230
Jeannette is somebody who cares
deeply about reading and education

00:01:59.230 --> 00:02:00.530
for children and is working

00:02:00.530 --> 00:02:02.980
on putting together the first
Book Festival in Ruanda,

00:02:02.980 --> 00:02:05.480
so thank you very much
for coming this evening.

00:02:05.480 --> 00:02:10.190
All of us know that we could be
doing something else this evening

00:02:10.190 --> 00:02:12.470
and all of us know that
it's a special weekend.

00:02:12.470 --> 00:02:15.970
And it's been my view for a
long time that people who go

00:02:15.970 --> 00:02:19.440
to Book Festivals are
likely to live longer.

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:23.300
[laughter] And to have
a healthier life.

00:02:23.300 --> 00:02:27.280
Now that's my observation, I
can't prove it, but it is my -

00:02:27.280 --> 00:02:31.610
I do have it on good authority
that those who go to Book Festivals

00:02:31.610 --> 00:02:35.960
on holiday weekends have a special
place in heaven reserved for them.

00:02:35.960 --> 00:02:39.510
[laughter] Now, again,
I can't prove that.

00:02:39.510 --> 00:02:44.050
[ Applause ]

00:02:44.050 --> 00:02:46.490
So as you talk today or tomorrow
to your friends who are off

00:02:46.490 --> 00:02:48.770 position:56%
to the Hamptons or Martha's Vineyard

00:02:48.770 --> 00:02:51.130
or Nantucket you should let them
know that there's a special place

00:02:51.130 --> 00:02:56.440
in heaven reserved for you and
they're not going to have it.

00:02:56.440 --> 00:02:57.740
[laughter] It's hard to believe

00:02:57.740 --> 00:03:01.280
that this Book Festival
is only 15 years old.

00:03:01.280 --> 00:03:04.610
It seems like a tradition that's
gone on for 50 years or longer,

00:03:04.610 --> 00:03:06.560
but it's only 15 years, honestly.

00:03:06.560 --> 00:03:10.840
It was in 2001 that the
first Book Festival was held.

00:03:10.840 --> 00:03:14.880
There were 40 authors and there
were about 30,000 people attended.

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:18.730
It was quite an event,
never had been done before.

00:03:18.730 --> 00:03:23.890
This year we have 170 authors and
we expect well over 100,000 people

00:03:23.890 --> 00:03:26.380
on a Labor Day weekend,
which is extraordinary.

00:03:26.380 --> 00:03:29.300
So this is due to the work of a
lot of people and I'll mention some

00:03:29.300 --> 00:03:30.620
of those in a moment,

00:03:30.620 --> 00:03:34.380
but the festival tomorrow
we will have 12 hours

00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:35.840
of round-the-clock programming.

00:03:35.840 --> 00:03:39.660
Doors open at nine, from 10 o'clock
to 10 o'clock we're programmed,

00:03:39.660 --> 00:03:42.870
there are hundreds and
hundreds and hundreds of events.

00:03:42.870 --> 00:03:45.340
And anybody that cares
about reading and books

00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:48.570
and literacy will have
a great time there.

00:03:48.570 --> 00:03:51.130
Now The Library of Congress,
itself, for those who may not be

00:03:51.130 --> 00:03:54.500
that familiar with it, has
grown a fair bit as well

00:03:54.500 --> 00:03:57.150
since it's very modest beginning.

00:03:57.150 --> 00:04:01.280
The Library of Congress was an idea
that James Madison had around 1783,

00:04:01.280 --> 00:04:04.440
but Congress didn't really get
around to doing anything about it

00:04:04.440 --> 00:04:07.980
until 1800 when legislation
was passed

00:04:07.980 --> 00:04:10.700
to move the Capitol
officially to Washington,

00:04:10.700 --> 00:04:13.950
D.C. as part of that
legislation there was a provision

00:04:13.950 --> 00:04:18.490
in the legislation to have a
Library of Congress and all

00:04:18.490 --> 00:04:21.760
of $5,000 was appropriated for it.

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:23.320
But the appropriation
actually occurred,

00:04:23.320 --> 00:04:24.790
it wasn't a continuing resolution.

00:04:24.790 --> 00:04:33.280
[laughter] And that $5,000 was used
to buy 740 books and three maps,

00:04:33.280 --> 00:04:35.020
and that was for awhile
the collection

00:04:35.020 --> 00:04:36.710
of The Library of Congress.

00:04:36.710 --> 00:04:40.760
As we all know, in 1812 some
people from another part

00:04:40.760 --> 00:04:45.220
of the Atlantic came to
Washington and did some things

00:04:45.220 --> 00:04:47.380
that they probably now regret.

00:04:47.380 --> 00:04:51.630
One of those things was
burning The Library of Congress.

00:04:51.630 --> 00:04:56.160
At that time The Library of
Congress really had no books left

00:04:56.160 --> 00:05:00.910 position:56%
and then Thomas Jefferson, who was a
great fan of The Library of Congress

00:05:00.910 --> 00:05:04.630
and a great bibliophile offered to
sell his collection to The Library

00:05:04.630 --> 00:05:07.700
of Congress and ultimately
the negotiations went forward

00:05:07.700 --> 00:05:11.990
and happened, though interestingly
there were some people in Congress

00:05:11.990 --> 00:05:13.580
who debated it because they thought

00:05:13.580 --> 00:05:15.770
that Thomas Jefferson
really didn't believe in God

00:05:15.770 --> 00:05:18.990
and if we bought his collection
there would be anti-God books

00:05:18.990 --> 00:05:20.530
in the collection.

00:05:20.530 --> 00:05:23.430
So they went through every
single title before they agreed

00:05:23.430 --> 00:05:24.770
to buy the collection.

00:05:24.770 --> 00:05:31.850
They bought it for about $23,950
and he sold about 6,487 volumes,

00:05:31.850 --> 00:05:34.980
and that was The Library of
Congress collection for awhile.

00:05:34.980 --> 00:05:40.180
Then in 1851 another tragic
event happened, there was a fire

00:05:40.180 --> 00:05:45.070
in The Library of Congress, 55,000
volumes were then in The Library

00:05:45.070 --> 00:05:48.660
of Congress and about
two-thirds of them were destroyed

00:05:48.660 --> 00:05:51.660
and about two-thirds of
Thomas Jefferson's collection

00:05:51.660 --> 00:05:52.960
was destroyed.

00:05:52.960 --> 00:05:56.890
Now we're celebrating this year the
200th Anniversary of the purchase

00:05:56.890 --> 00:06:00.480 position:56%
of Thomas Jefferson's collection and
while all of those books aren't here

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:03.570
because of that fire in
1851, through the leadership

00:06:03.570 --> 00:06:06.460
of Jim Billington and others
we have restored virtually all

00:06:06.460 --> 00:06:09.020
of those books, not the
originals from Thomas Jefferson,

00:06:09.020 --> 00:06:11.920
but the same volumes and they
are here and you can see them

00:06:11.920 --> 00:06:13.220
at any time and you'll be able

00:06:13.220 --> 00:06:15.000
to see them this evening
if you're interested.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:19.100
So this is the 200th Anniversary
of that historic collection

00:06:19.100 --> 00:06:20.650
and purchase from Thomas Jefferson.

00:06:20.650 --> 00:06:25.680
I want to thank Jim Billington
later and I want to mention him

00:06:25.680 --> 00:06:27.550
in a few other remarks
I want to make,

00:06:27.550 --> 00:06:31.280 position:56%
but Jim Billington is really the
father of the National Book Festival

00:06:31.280 --> 00:06:33.810
and I will mention him
in passing in a moment.

00:06:33.810 --> 00:06:35.620
But I just want to
acknowledge that, Jim,

00:06:35.620 --> 00:06:40.060
I know that this will probably be
your last time as the Librarian

00:06:40.060 --> 00:06:42.550
of Congress presiding over
a National Book Festival

00:06:42.550 --> 00:06:43.850
and there are other people
who are going to talk

00:06:43.850 --> 00:06:46.290
about you this evening, and
I just want to say personally

00:06:46.290 --> 00:06:48.170
that I have enjoyed working
with you extraordinarily.

00:06:48.170 --> 00:06:49.930
It's been one of the
great privileges

00:06:49.930 --> 00:06:51.360
of my life to get to know you.

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:53.090
You've done a great
job for the country.

00:06:53.090 --> 00:06:57.510
I can't imagine we would ever have
a better Librarian of Congress.

00:06:57.510 --> 00:07:05.150
[ Applause ]

00:07:05.150 --> 00:07:08.610
But shortly somebody with far
greater eloquence than I will talk

00:07:08.610 --> 00:07:10.060
about Jim Billington in the ways

00:07:10.060 --> 00:07:14.930
that I think are worth
listening to, shortly.

00:07:14.930 --> 00:07:17.870
So I want to thank the sponsors who
made this possible this evening.

00:07:17.870 --> 00:07:21.540 position:56%
Let me mention them -- Wells Fargo,
which has been very, very supportive

00:07:21.540 --> 00:07:25.980
of The Library of Congress
National Book Festival, AARP,

00:07:25.980 --> 00:07:31.160
The Institute of Museum and Library
Services, The Washington Post,

00:07:31.160 --> 00:07:33.420
The Madison Council and NEA.

00:07:33.420 --> 00:07:37.140
And as a result of their
gifts in kind and cash

00:07:37.140 --> 00:07:41.180 position:56%
and other things we are able to have
the National Book Festival for free.

00:07:41.180 --> 00:07:42.930
And I'm committed to
making certain that as long

00:07:42.930 --> 00:07:44.660
as I'm involved it
will always be for free

00:07:44.660 --> 00:07:47.720
and I think it's a great thing for
the American people that we make it

00:07:47.720 --> 00:07:50.890
for free, and so everybody who
wants to come tomorrow doesn't have

00:07:50.890 --> 00:07:54.150
to worry about cost and
it's an extraordinary event,

00:07:54.150 --> 00:07:57.890
unlike anything really that I've
seen anywhere else in the world

00:07:57.890 --> 00:07:59.460
in terms of a Book Festival.

00:07:59.460 --> 00:08:04.510
So I would like to
just say that Jim ...

00:08:04.510 --> 00:08:10.330
[ Applause ]

00:08:10.330 --> 00:08:12.710
... how did we actually
come to this Book Festival,

00:08:12.710 --> 00:08:15.770
how did it actually come about.

00:08:15.770 --> 00:08:20.110
Well, many different ways
that you can look at it,

00:08:20.110 --> 00:08:24.380
but victory has a thousand
fathers and defeat is an orphan,

00:08:24.380 --> 00:08:28.550
it is often said, and
this is a victory.

00:08:28.550 --> 00:08:31.390
But really there are only two
people that deserve the credit

00:08:31.390 --> 00:08:32.690
for getting this off the ground.

00:08:32.690 --> 00:08:37.930
At the time of the Inaugural
festivities of George W. Bush,

00:08:37.930 --> 00:08:40.360
Laura Bush mentioned to the
Librarian in the Congress,

00:08:40.360 --> 00:08:43.560
Jim Billington, that there
had been a Texas Book Festival

00:08:43.560 --> 00:08:46.320
that she had helped to
start and she wanted

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:48.580
to know was there a
National Book Festival?

00:08:48.580 --> 00:08:52.860
And Jim Billington said, well,
there isn't yet, but there will be.

00:08:52.860 --> 00:08:55.900
And Jim Billington then
began to work very closely

00:08:55.900 --> 00:09:01.340 position:56%
with Laura Bush and, well, why don't
we let her tell you more about it.

00:09:04.850 --> 00:09:06.620
&gt;&gt; Laura Bush: Good
evening and welcome

00:09:06.620 --> 00:09:10.140
to the 15th National
Book Festival's Gala,

00:09:10.140 --> 00:09:13.570
on the eve of our very first
National Book Festival.

00:09:13.570 --> 00:09:18.190
On Friday, September 7th,
2001wegathered right here

00:09:18.190 --> 00:09:21.650
in the Coolidge Auditorium
of The Library of Congress

00:09:21.650 --> 00:09:25.070
to begin what we hoped
would become a new tradition

00:09:25.070 --> 00:09:26.750
in our nation's Capitol.

00:09:26.750 --> 00:09:30.560
President Bush, many members of
his Cabinet, and a marvelous group

00:09:30.560 --> 00:09:33.800
of authors and book
lovers, just like you,

00:09:33.800 --> 00:09:37.020
were here to help launch
what has since become one

00:09:37.020 --> 00:09:40.850
of the most successful Book
Festivals in the world.

00:09:40.850 --> 00:09:44.090 position:56%
I am proud to have worked
alongside the Librarian of Congress,

00:09:44.090 --> 00:09:48.530
Dr. James Billington, and
his excellent staff to bring

00:09:48.530 --> 00:09:51.170
to Washington a National
Book Festival.

00:09:51.170 --> 00:09:56.040
As a lifelong lover of books
and a librarian I believe

00:09:56.040 --> 00:09:59.700
that children everywhere
should learn to read and I know

00:09:59.700 --> 00:10:03.660
that literacy is an essential
foundation for democracy.

00:10:03.660 --> 00:10:05.430
And like Thomas Jefferson,

00:10:05.430 --> 00:10:11.010
who 200 years ago sent his lifetime
collection of books to be housed

00:10:11.010 --> 00:10:17.530
in the building where you now sit,
I too cannot live without books.

00:10:17.530 --> 00:10:20.720
So it's a special joy to
welcome you here tonight

00:10:20.720 --> 00:10:24.640
to celebrate the 15th Anniversary
of the National Book Festival.

00:10:24.640 --> 00:10:29.650
Thank you, Dr. Billington, for your
service as our nation's Librarian.

00:10:29.650 --> 00:10:33.150
Thank you to The Library
of Congress, the largest,

00:10:33.150 --> 00:10:36.470
most vibrant Library in the world.

00:10:36.470 --> 00:10:39.470
Thank you to all the friends
of The Library of Congress.

00:10:39.470 --> 00:10:43.140
Happy 200th Birthday to
our national treasure,

00:10:43.140 --> 00:10:45.360
the Thomas Jefferson Collection.

00:10:45.360 --> 00:10:48.880
And Happy Birthday to yet
another American treasure,

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:52.510
the National Book Festival.

00:10:52.510 --> 00:11:00.040
[ Applause ]

