00:31:30.570 --> 00:31:34.730
trying to use a longer lens
writing narrative military history,

00:31:34.730 --> 00:31:37.380
every scribbler since Eucides
[Assumed Spelling] knows

00:31:37.380 --> 00:31:42.600 position:56%
that writing about war means
writing about love, valor, venality,

00:31:42.600 --> 00:31:47.400 position:56%
the foolishness of fools, the
knavery of knaves, the whole panoply

00:31:47.400 --> 00:31:50.810
of human behavior and misbehavior.

00:31:52.560 --> 00:31:57.120
In early 2003 between books I did
some backsliding into journalism

00:31:57.120 --> 00:32:00.850
and went off to war, from Fort
Campbell, Kentucky to Iraq

00:32:00.850 --> 00:32:04.920
with the 101st Airborne
Division, then commanded

00:32:04.920 --> 00:32:08.910
by my non West Point
classmate, Dave Petraeus.

00:32:08.910 --> 00:32:12.520
One day just after the
invasion began Petraeus

00:32:12.520 --> 00:32:16.820
and I were standing outside
in a screaming sandstorm

00:32:16.820 --> 00:32:19.420
in a remote hellhole
of Southern Iraq,

00:32:19.420 --> 00:32:22.850
our faces no more than
eight inches apart.

00:32:22.850 --> 00:32:27.140
Things were not going very well
in the war, not very well at all.

00:32:27.140 --> 00:32:36.910
And he said tell me how this
ends, tell me how this ends?

00:32:36.910 --> 00:32:42.110
I recently finished writing 750,000
words about the American role

00:32:42.110 --> 00:32:44.770
in the liberation of
Europe in World War II.

00:32:44.770 --> 00:32:47.860
We just commemorated on
Wednesday the 70th Anniversary

00:32:47.860 --> 00:32:49.670
of the formal end of the War.

00:32:49.670 --> 00:32:51.960 position:56%
Oddly enough during the home stretch

00:32:51.960 --> 00:32:56.170
that question perplexed
me, tell me how this ends?

00:32:56.170 --> 00:32:59.790
Authors know that finding an
ending can be as difficult

00:32:59.790 --> 00:33:01.910
as finding a beginning sometimes.

00:33:01.910 --> 00:33:04.700
We all know how World
War II ends, right?

00:33:04.700 --> 00:33:09.770
Ticker tape, America ascendant,
boom and post-war babies,

00:33:09.770 --> 00:33:13.250
some of whom are sitting
in this room tonight.

00:33:13.250 --> 00:33:18.930
But then I came across a document
compiled by the US Army in 1946

00:33:18.930 --> 00:33:24.170
that suggested how to put a
period on those 750,000 words.

00:33:24.170 --> 00:33:29.590
The document recounted in exquisite
detail how in a large warehouse

00:33:29.590 --> 00:33:35.920
at 601 Hardesty Avenue in Kansas
City the US Army Effects Bureau had

00:33:35.920 --> 00:33:39.090
begun as a modest quartermaster
operation

00:33:39.090 --> 00:33:44.340
with a half dozen employees
in February 1942.

00:33:44.340 --> 00:33:46.880
That expanded to more
than 1,000 workers,

00:33:46.880 --> 00:33:52.050
and by August 1945 they were
handling 60,000 shipments a month,

00:33:52.050 --> 00:33:57.450
each laden with the effects of
American dead from six continents.

00:33:57.450 --> 00:34:03.250
Hour after hour, day after day
shipping containers were unloaded

00:34:03.250 --> 00:34:07.470
on to a receiving dock and
then hoisted by elevator

00:34:07.470 --> 00:34:10.080
to the Depot's 10th floor.

00:34:10.080 --> 00:34:15.580
Here the containers traveled by
assembly line, conveyor belt,

00:34:15.580 --> 00:34:22.630 position:56%
down to the 7th floor, as inspectors
pawed through each container

00:34:22.630 --> 00:34:28.210
to extract pornography,
ammunition, perhaps amorous letters

00:34:28.210 --> 00:34:32.630
from a girlfriend you didn't
want a grieving widow to see.

00:34:32.630 --> 00:34:39.120 position:56%
Workers used grinding stones and
dentist drills to remove bloodstains

00:34:39.120 --> 00:34:41.690
and corrosion from
helmets and web gear.

00:34:41.690 --> 00:34:44.080 position:56%
A detailed inventory was then pinned

00:34:44.080 --> 00:34:49.590
to each repacked container before
it was stacked in a storage bin.

00:34:49.590 --> 00:34:56.100 position:56%
And all the while in a huge adjacent
room banks of typists were banging

00:34:56.100 --> 00:35:01.620
out letters, up to 70,000 letters
a month by December of 1945,

00:35:01.620 --> 00:35:07.660
and the gist of those letters
was this - Dear Sir, Dear Madam,

00:35:07.660 --> 00:35:10.860
we have your dead son's stuff,

00:35:10.860 --> 00:35:16.470
you want it back, where
should we send it?

00:35:16.470 --> 00:35:22.180
Over the years the Effects Bureau,
inspectors found amazing things -

00:35:22.180 --> 00:35:28.660
tapestries, enemy swords, a
German machinegun, walrus tusks,

00:35:28.660 --> 00:35:32.150
a shrunken head, a tobacco
sack full of diamonds.

00:35:32.150 --> 00:35:35.040
Among thousands of
diaries also collected

00:35:35.040 --> 00:35:38.490
in Kansas City was a black
notebook that belonged

00:35:38.490 --> 00:35:43.740
to Lieutenant Herschel G. Horton,
29 years old from Aurora, Illinois.

00:35:43.740 --> 00:35:47.240
Shot in the leg and hip during
a firefight with a Japanese

00:35:47.240 --> 00:35:51.640
on New Guinea, he had dragged
himself into a grass shanty.

00:35:51.640 --> 00:35:53.580
And in the several days
that it took for him

00:35:53.580 --> 00:35:57.500
to die he wrote a final
letter home to his family.

00:35:57.500 --> 00:36:03.330
And it began -- My Dear Sweet
Father, Mother and Sister,

00:36:03.330 --> 00:36:09.380
I lay here in this terrible place
wondering not why God has forsaken

00:36:09.380 --> 00:36:12.900
me, but why he is making me suffer.

00:36:12.900 --> 00:36:21.080
That's how it ends,
that's how it always ends.

00:36:21.080 --> 00:36:25.090
And I'll end this evening, since
we are in The Library of Congress

00:36:25.090 --> 00:36:28.700
by quoting our recent Poet
Laureate, Natasha Trethewey,

00:36:28.700 --> 00:36:33.240 position:56%
who ends her poem, Pilgrimage,
which is about a visit to Vicksburg,

00:36:33.240 --> 00:36:38.880
with these lines - In my dream
the ghost of history lies

00:36:38.880 --> 00:36:46.770
down beside me, rolls over,
pins me beneath a heavy arm.

00:36:46.770 --> 00:36:51.970
My job is to make the
reader feel that heavy arm.

00:36:51.970 --> 00:36:54.950
Thanks very much for the privilege
of being with you this evening.

00:36:54.950 --> 00:36:56.750
Thank you.

